08477nam a22011175i 9780812204643DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013954435  a(OCoLC)979684716  a97808122046437 a10.9783/97808122046432doi  a(DE-B1597)449358  a(OCoLC)793012543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHB3722b.C696 2011eb 7aBUS0360002bisacsh04a330.9/051122200aCorporate Governance Failures :bThe Role of Institutional Investors in the Global Financial Crisis /ced. by James P. Hawley, Andrew T. Williams, Shyam J. Kamath. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b22 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Beyond Risk: Notes Toward a Responsible Investment Theory -- tChapter 3. The Quality of Corporate Governance Within Financial Firms in Stressed Markets -- tChapter 4. Chasing Alpha: An Ideological Explanation of the Catastrophic Failure in the U.K.'s Financial Services Industry -- tChapter 5. Corporate Governance, Risk Analysis, and the Financial Crisis: Did Universal Owners Contribute to the Crisis? -- tChapter 6. Great Expectations: Institutional Investors, Executive Remuneration, and ‘‘Say on Pay’’ -- tChapter 7. Against Stupidity, the Gods Themselves Contend in Vain: The Limits of Corporate Governance in Dealing with Asset Bubbles -- tChapter 8. Real Estate, Governance, and the Global Economic Crisis -- tChapter 9. The Sophisticated Investor and the Global Financial Crisis -- tChapter 10. The Role of Investment Consultants in Transforming Pension Fund Decision Making: The Integration of Environmental, Social, and Governance Considerations into Corporate Valuation -- tChapter 11. Funding Climate Change: How Pension Fund Fiduciary Duty Masks Trustee Inertia and Short-Termism -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCorporate governance, the internal policies and leadership that guide the actions of corporations, played a major part in the recent global financial crisis. While much blame has been targeted at compensation arrangements that rewarded extreme risk-taking but did not punish failure, the performance of large, supposedly sophisticated institutional investors in this crisis has gone for the most part unexamined. Shareholding organizations, such as pension funds and mutual funds, hold considerable sway over the financial industry from Wall Street to the City of London. Corporate Governance Failures: The Role of Institutional Investors in the Global Financial Crisis exposes the misdeeds and lapses of these institutional investors leading up to the recent economic meltdown.In this collection of original essays, edited by pioneers in the field of fiduciary capitalism, top legal and financial practitioners and researchers discuss detrimental actions and inaction of institutional investors. Corporate Governance Failures reveals how these organizations exposed themselves and their clientele to extremely complex financial instruments, such as credit default swaps, through investments in hedge and private equity funds as well as more traditional equity investments in large financial institutions. The book's contributors critique fund executives for tolerating the "pursuit of alpha" culture that led managers to pursue risky financial strategies in hopes of outperforming the market. The volume also points out how and why institutional investors failed to effectively monitor such volatile investments, ignoring relatively well-established corporate governance principles and best practices.Along with detailed investigations of institutional investor missteps, Corporate Governance Failures offers nuanced and realistic proposals to mitigate future financial pitfalls. This volume provides fresh perspectives on ways institutional investors can best act as gatekeepers and promote responsible investment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCorporate governance -- Congresses. 0aCorporate governancevCongresses. 0aFinancial risk -- Congresses. 0aFinancial riskvCongresses. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009 -- Congresses. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009vCongresses. 0aInstitutional investments -- Congresses. 0aInstitutional investmentsvCongresses. 4aPolitical Science. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Investments & Securities / General.2bisacsh  aBusiness.  aEconomics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aAugar, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Adam D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDravis, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichholtz, Piet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawley, James P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawley, James P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKamath, Shyam J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamath, Shyam J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnight, Eric R. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKok, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLydenberg, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheehan, Kym, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaub, Jennifer S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular